  "slug": "nougat-soft-honey",
  "title": "Soft honey nougat",
  "subtitle": "Chewy honey-scented nougat with toasted almonds and pistachios",
  "excerpt": "Twenty-four pieces of soft nougat: honey cooked to 121°C and poured into whipped egg whites, followed by a caster sugar and glucose syrup cooked to 145°C, beaten until chewy and white, then folded through with warm toasted almonds and pistachios and pressed into a lined tin.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Soft nougat (nougat blanc or nougat de Montélimar) is documented in French and Italian confectionery from the nineteenth century. Auguste Escoffier, Le Guide Culinaire (1903): the nougat section documents the two-syrup method, where honey is cooked to soft-ball stage and poured into egg whites, followed by a firmer sugar syrup, as the technique for producing a soft, chewy nougat with a stable aerated structure. The addition of toasted almonds and pistachios is documented in both French and Italian public-domain confectionery literature of the period. The recipe here follows the two-syrup public-domain method.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Soft honey nougat is a chewy, pale confection of honey, sugar, and egg whites, flavoured with vanilla and studded with toasted nuts. Two separate syrups go into the whipped egg whites in sequence: the honey syrup first at 121°C, which sets the aeration; the sugar syrup second at 145°C, which firms the structure. The result is chewy rather than hard, and the honey perfumes the whole batch. Add the nuts warm, straight from the oven, so they fold in without cooling the nougat too fast."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
